These features are important indicators of spin physics, but the challenges associated with data quality and availability, as well as the subtlety of the physical phenomena of interest, have hindered the development of an automatic and customized analysis framework, which often still relies on human labeling and verification.
In this study, we introduce a feature extraction framework for bias triangles, which is built on unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision methods. This framework enables the direct identification and quantification of physical properties of the former, without the need for human input or large training datasets to inform supervised learning approaches.
In particular, we demonstrate that Pauli spin blockade (PSB) detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently, and without any training data as a direct result of this approach.
